The fluorescence intensity varies slightly depending on the ionic strength (Fig. 6
                        ). Therefore, the salt content of the sample will not have a significant effect on the optical properties. The data suggest that the obtained sensor can be used for real samples. In the next part of the research, the stability of carbon dots used as a sensor was investigated to determine when fluorescence of CDs in medium (buffer) would have a constant value and for how long the sensor should be incubated with the analyte to receive the maximum quenching effect. The tests demonstrated that carbon dot fluorescence stabilized after 20 min and its quenching by Hg2+ was highest at 25 min. Thus the time of 25 min is optimal for such sensors (Fig. 7
                        ).
